# <%= current_page.data.title %>
 
## Purpose of TDA
The Technical Design Authority ensures that all technology designs across MHCLG are:

* Compliant with the Government Technology Code of Practice (TCoP)
* Aligned with MHCLG technology strategy and standards
* Designed securely, sustainably, and following good architectural practice

TDA does not:

* Approve spend
* Provide security assurance
* Manage routine change (CAB does this)

## What Happens During the Review Meeting
### Before the Meeting

* Your submission is circulated to TDA members.
* It must be submitted one week before the meeting (Thursday).
* Late submissions lose their slot.

### During the Meeting

You will:

* Present a summary slide (PowerPoint)
* Walk through key design decisions
* Demonstrate technical artefacts (architecture diagrams, workflows, etc.)
* Answer questions from:
    * Technical Architects
    * Cyber Security Leads
    * Digital Delivery
    * Data & Information Management specialists
    * Additional specialists depending on scope

Panels typically probe: risks, security, data, sustainability, compliance, support model, cost clarity.

## After the Meeting

Outcome will be one of:

* Approval
* Conditional approval
* Non‑approval

You will also receive:

* A written list of actions (if applicable)
* Actions issued within 2–3 working days
* Action tracking managed by PMO

## What the Panel Is Looking For

### Clear Reason for Submission

Accepted triggers:

* New system or capability
* Significant change to existing systems
* Architectural change
* New risks or external exposure

## User Need & Objectives

Panels expect:

* Clear definition of users
* Defined user needs
* A rationale showing how the design meets those needs

### Coherent Solution Overview

Include:

* End‑to‑end architecture
* Integrations and key components
* Data flows
* Hosting choice and rationale
* Identified constraints and trade‑offs

### TCoP Compliance

* Demonstrate compliance with all 13 TCoP points.
* Weak or missing justification is a common cause of conditional approval.

### Security & Privacy Evidence

Required:

* System risk assessment
* Data classifications and handling
* Security controls in place
* Cyber Security and DPA engagement

### Risk Management

Panels validate:

* Risks identified
* Mitigations realistic and complete
* Residual risks with clear owners

### Value for Money

Panels expect:

* Transparent cost model
* Efficiency and justification of spend

### Support & Operational Readiness

Explain:

* Support after go‑live
* Monitoring and logging
* Release management

### Adoption & Change Management

Demonstrate readiness:

* Communications
* Training
* Change impact assessments

## Tips for a High‑Quality TDA Submission

### Follow the Template Exactly

The TORs state:
“Any submissions that do not follow the template will be rejected and the team stand the chance to lose their slot.”

### Provide Artefacts Early

Submit early:

* System design docs
* Architecture diagrams
* Risk assessments
* TCoP responses

### Provide a Balanced Options Appraisal

Each option requires:

* Description
* Benefits
* Disadvantages
* Risks

Panels strongly dislike single‑option submissions.

### Make Security a First‑Class Citizen

Checklist requires evidence of:

* Security controls
* Cyber team sign‑off
* Data Protection sign‑off

### Include Clear Architecture Diagrams

Recommended diagram types:

* High‑level context
* Component views
* Data flow diagrams
* Deployment architecture

### Address Future‑Proofing & Sustainability

Panels often ask:

“How will this evolve? Does it avoid vendor lock‑in?”

### Dependencies

Clearly document:

* Inter‑team dependencies
* Required sign‑offs
* Dependencies on evolving platforms (e.g., Data 4 Insights)

### Support Model

Explain:

* Monitoring, alerting, logging
* Support tiers
* Runbooks

### Verbal Summary

Be concise and cover:

* Problem
* Solution
* Risks & mitigations
* Security
* Cost
* “What you need from TDA”

## What “Good” Looks Like

A high‑quality submission:

* Has no empty sections
* Shows cross‑department collaboration
* Demonstrates TCoP due diligence
* Justifies architectural decisions
* Includes diagrams
* Demonstrates credible risk management
* Clearly states approval request or needed guidance

## TDA Governance FAQs

### Purpose of TDA
The TDA:

* Approves MHCLG technology strategy, policies, and standards
* Ensures alignment to TCoP
* Provides early guidance to project and service teams

TDA does not:

* Approve spend
* Provide security assurance
* Manage routine change (CAB)

### Roles Represented on the Panel

* Head of Technology (Chair)
* Technical Architect
* Digital Tools Lead
* Cyber Security Lead
* Digital Delivery Lead
* Enterprise Data Architect
* Cyber Security Architect
* TDA Coordinator
* Data Protection
* Information Management
* CDP / CDO representatives
* SAP, DAP, PINS technical architects

## When Should Something Go to TDA?

Submit when:

* Delivering a new system or capability
* Making significant changes to existing systems
* Introducing new architecture
* Creating external exposure or new risks

Also recommended:

* Programme roadmap walkthroughs (Datamart, SAP, Digital Land)

## Pre‑TDA Process (Order of Activities)

### Book a slot early (≥ 3 weeks before meeting)

### Prepare and submit:

* System design & architecture diagrams
* System risk assessment
* TCoP responses
* Submit papers/slides by Thursday the week before
* Ensure template compliance
* Attend the meeting and present

## Booking a TDA Slot

* Book via booking app ≥ 3 weeks before meeting
* Submit documents by Thursday the week prior
* Email submissions to TDAmeeting@communities.gov.uk

Example timeline:

* TDA date: 29 May
* Request slot by: 8 May
* Submit papers by: 23 May
